ducation with hyper-individualistic models and practices that hinder the ability of Catholic institutions to create an environment imbued with bedrock values and principles of Catholic Social Teaching such as respect for human rights, solidarity, and justice. Beyer problematizes corporatized higher education and shows how it has adversely affected efforts at Catholic schools to promote worker justice on campus; equitable admissions; financial aid; retention policies; diversity and inclusion policies that treat people of color, women, and LGBTQ persons as full community members; just investment; and stewardship of resources and the environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCatholic universities and collegeszUnited States. 0aChristian sociologyxCatholic Church. 0aSocial justice and education. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh  aCatholic higher education.  aCatholic social teaching corporatization.  aLGBTQ students, worker justice.  acollege access.  acontingency.  ajust universities, gender parity.  aracial equity.  asocially responsible investment.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2021 Englishz978311075406308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2021z9783110753950oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073909140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823289998zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823289998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9